China has announced a 14% increase in the number of citizens living with HIV or AIDS.
According to health officials, more than 820.000 people are affected in the country.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, approximately 40,000 new cases were reported.
Unlike in the past, the transmission took place in the vast majority of new cases through sexual intercourse.
So far, HIV has spread rapidly in some parts of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people infected with HIV in this way has been reduced to almost zero, Chinese health officials said at a conference in Yunnan province.
Compared to the year, however, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS has increased by 100,000 in China.
HIV transmission through sexual intercourse is an acute problem in China’s LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT members is said to be widespread.
Based on the country’s conservative values, studies estimate that 70-90% of men who have sex with men eventually marry women.
Many of the disease transmissions are due to insufficient protection during sexual intercourse in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised, among other things, general access to HIV medicines to address the problem.
