Syria is ‘ready’ for return of refugees, says foreign minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild the country devastated by the seven-year war.
In a speech before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that the situation in the country is improving.
“Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government is rebuilding the areas destroyed by terrorists to bring back normality.
All the conditions have now been laid for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they had to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and bases of life.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
A further six million people still living in the country need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian government welcomed aid in the reconstruction of the devastated country.
He stressed, however, that there would be no conditions-related assistance from countries that had supported the uprising.
Europe wins Ryder Cup in Paris
Team Europa won the 2018 Ryder Cup and defeated Team USA with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National near Paris.
The United States has now lost six consecutive times on European soil and has not won a Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe won the crown back after the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn reached the 14.5 points it needed to defeat the United States.
American star Phil Mickelson, who had problems over much of the tournament, drowned his run on the 16th track (Par 3) in the water and lost to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari was able to shine in all of his rounds and became one of 4 players who scored 5-0-0 since the tournament began in its current format in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth was defeated 5:4 by the player with the lowest ranking in the team Europe, Thorbjorn Olesen from Denmark.
The player with the world’s best ranking, Dustin Johnson, lost 2-1 to England’s Ian Poulter, who may have played his last Ryder Cup.
Spanish Sergio Garcia, a veteran of eight Ryder Cups, became the best European Ryder Cup player of all time with 25.5 career points.
“Normally I don’t cry, but today I couldn’t hold back.
