Red Tide Update: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota Decreasing
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows that there is a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, in the areas of the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, more lacking flowering conditions are recorded, indicating decreasing concentrations.
A red algae bloom extends over approximately 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinellas to the south of the Lee district.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but compared to the previous week in fewer places.
A red tide was also observed in the Pasco district.
In the past week, median concentrations have been reported in or off the coast of the Pinellas district, low to high concentrations off the coast of the Manatee district, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of the Charlotte district, background to high concentrations in the centre of the Col in or off the coast of Letri Bezier.
Breathing disorders continue to be reported from the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier districts.
In northwestern Florida, no new respiratory problems have been reported during the past week.
